Blogpocalipsis
Lo vi en <a href="http://www.ecuaderno.com/2006/01/18/blogpocalypse/">Blogpocalypse</a> y apunta a <a href="http://www.admodumdigirati.com/45/who-will-survive-the-blogpocalypse/"> Who will survive the blogpocalypse?</a>.

Es de hace semanas, pero con lo que se está diciendo estos días, supongo
que sigue teniendo actualidad:

<blockquote>
Just to hurl some random statistics at you for fun, of the forty most popular feeds on Bloglines, twenty four are established websites that long predate the blognomenon (giggle). Eight of them are the websites of print publications that predate the internet, of those eight, one predates television (BBC), two predate the internal combustion engine (NY Times & Scientific American) and one predates the typewriter (The Guardian)
</blockquote>

¿Sólo puede quedar una? (una clase de sitios web, se entiende...)

Aunque, como nos decía Simon Dumenco, que un bitacorero sólo es un escritor con un nombre 'pijo': <a href="http://www.adage.com/mediaworks/article?article_id=48098">A Blogger is Just a Writer with a Cooler Name</a> (visto en <a href="http://mangasverdes.es/2006/01/19/un-blogger-no-es-mas-que-un-escritor-con-nombre-cool/">Un blogger no es más que un escritor con nombre cool</a>.

<blockquote>
And it occurred to me that there is no such thing as blogging. There is no such thing as a blogger. Blogging is just writing -- writing using a particularly efficient type of publishing technology. Even though I tend to first use Microsoft Word on the way to being published, I am not, say, a Worder or Wordder.
</blockquote>


